# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aloo-tikki
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aloo-tikki/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] A **3-in-1**, **trio** or **three-in-one** is a fast-food dish consisting of chips, boiled rice (or egg fried rice), and curry sauce served in a single foil tray or plastic container.
[src:aloo-tikki/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] It became popular in Ireland as a dish from chip shops and Chinese restaurants in the early twenty-first century.
[src:aloo-tikki/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] It developed a cult following in the 2010s, and media outlets debated the merits of it compared to a spice bag, which became popular around the same time.
[src:aloo-tikki/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] Related dishes (four-, five-in one) contain additional ingredients such as chicken balls, or chicken or beef pieces.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Other akara types includes Akara Awon (from beans and okro) and Egusi Akara (made from egusi seeds).
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Another type of Akara product is Akara Ogbomosho (Akara chips) which are crunchy chips.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Brazilian acarajé is made from raw and milled cowpeas that are seasoned with salt, pepper and chopped onions molded into the shape of a large scone and deep-fried in dendê with a wok-like pan in front of the customers.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] It is served split in half and stuffed with *vatapá* and *caruru* – spicy pastes made from shrimp, ground cashews, palm oil and other ingredients.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] A vegetarian version is typically served with hot peppers and green tomatoes.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Acarajé can also comes in a second form called abará, in which the nutritious ingredients are steamed instead of deep-fried, similar to moi moi.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Acarajé serves as both a religious offering to the gods in the Candomblé religion and as street food.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] In Sierra Leone, *akara* is composed of rice flour, mashed banana, baking powder, and sugar.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] After mixed together, it is dropped in oil by hand, and fried, similar to puff-puff.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] *Akara* is usually prepared for events like Pulnado (event held due to the birth of a child), a wedding, funeral, or party.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Acarajé sold on the street in Brazil are variously made with fried beef, mutton, dried shrimp, pigweed, fufu osun sauce, and coconut.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Today in Bahia, Brazil, most street vendors who serve acarajé are women, easily recognizable by their all-white cotton dresses and headscarves and caps.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] They first appeared in Bahia selling acarajé in the 19th century.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Earnings from the sale of acarajé were used both to buy the freedom of enslaved family members until the abolition of slavery in Brazil in 1888; its sale additionally served as a source of family income.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] The city now has more than 500 acarajé vendors.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] The image of these women, often simply called *baianas*, frequently appears in artwork from the region of Bahia.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Acarajé, however, is available outside of the state of Bahia as well, including the streets of its neighborboring state of Sergipe, and the markets of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Acarajé is essential ritual food used in Afro-Brazilian religious traditions such as Candomblé.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] The first acarajé in a Candomblé ritual is offered to the orixá Exu.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] They vary in size based on their offering to a specific deity: large, round acarajé are offered to Xangô; ones smaller in form are offered to Iansã.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Small, fritter-size acarajé are offered to Erê (deity), or child spirits.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Acarajé is used in Candomblé rituals in the states of Bahia, Rio de Janeiro, São Paulo, Pernambuco, Alagoas, Sergipe, and Maranhão.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] It is closely related to acaçá, a similar ritual food made of steamed corn mush.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Acarajé de azeite-doce is a variety of acarajé fried in an oil other than palm oil; olive oil or other vegetable oils are generally used.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Acarajé de azeite-doce is used in Candomblé offerings to orixás with a ritual prohibition of the use of palm oil.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] This variety is found in the states of Bahia and Rio de Janeiro.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Acarajé de Xangô (àkàrà tí Ṣàngó) is a variety of acarajé offered to the orixá Xangô, known as the òriṣà Ṣangó in the Yoruba culture.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] It is made of the same ingredients as the common form but greatly elongated.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] This variety is found on the ritual platter of amalá offered to Xangô.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] This variety is found in the state of Bahia and in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] Acarajé was listed as a national intangible historic heritage (*patrimônio nacional imaterial*), by the National Institute of Historic and Artistic Heritage in 2004; the role of *baianas* in the preparation and sale of acarajé was recognized in the same act.
[src:aloo-tikki/acarajé] In October 2023, Rio de Janeiro declared the fritter to be part of that city's cultural heritage.
[src:aloo-tikki/adhirasam] Adhirasam is a popular as an offering to the relatives during Deepavali and Ganesha Chaturthi festivals, both at home and in temples in Tamil Nadu and Karnataka.
[src:aloo-tikki/adhirasam] The earliest documented references to Adhirasam emerge from medieval Tamil kingdoms, particularly the Chola dynasty, where it appeared as a favored item in royal feasts and temple rituals.
[src:aloo-tikki/adhirasam] According to inscriptions from the 16th century, during the reign of Vijayanagara emperor Krishnadevaraya, the sweet was made from rice flour, jaggery, ghee and pepper.
[src:aloo-tikki/adhirasam] At the annual festival at the Panchavarnesvar Temple in Thirunallur (located near Kumbakonam, Tamil Nadu), an offering of 6000 Adhirasams along with 6000 vadas is made to the Gods; the entire lot is cooked in the temple kitchen between sunrise and 11 pm, for the prayers that take place at midnight.
[src:aloo-tikki/adhirasam] It is a popular Deepavali sweet preparation for Tamil people.
[src:aloo-tikki/adhirasam] The authentic preparation takes about a week.
[src:aloo-tikki/adhirasam] First the rice is soaked in water and dried in shade and ground into a fine powder when the rice is 3/4th dried and retains some moisture.
[src:aloo-tikki/adhirasam] For adding sweet "vellam" (jaggery in Tamil) is melted in water by boiling it till it reaches soft-ball consistency (235–240 °F (113–116 °C), if using a candy thermometer) and added to the rice flour along with some powdered cardamom to make a thick dough.
[src:aloo-tikki/adhirasam] It is then transferred to an earthenware pot and the top of the pot is closed with a thin white cloth.
[src:aloo-tikki/adhirasam] It is then allowed to ferment for about 3–5 days by placing it in the sunlight during the day.
[src:aloo-tikki/adhirasam] Finally, when the batter is ready for preparation, small balls of the dough is taken and flattened using fingers in a small piece of oil-brushed banana leaf and deep fried in oil until golden brown.
[src:aloo-tikki/adhirasam] Then it is pressed with a flat bottomed bowl to remove the excess oil.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] Pakistan is administratively divided into four provinces, one federal territory, and two disputed territories: the provinces of Punjab, Sindh, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, and Balochistan; the Islamabad Capital Territory; and the administrative territories of Azad Jammu and Kashmir and Gilgit–Baltistan.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] As part of the Kashmir conflict with neighbouring India, Pakistan has also claimed sovereignty over the Indian-controlled territories of Jammu and Kashmir and Ladakh since the First Kashmir War of 1947–1948.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] It also has a territorial dispute with India over Junagadh, but has never exercised administrative authority over either regions.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] All of Pakistan's provinces and territories are subdivided into divisions, which are further subdivided into districts, and then tehsils, which are again further subdivided into union councils.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] Pakistan inherited the territory comprising its current provinces from India following the Partition of India on 14 August 1947.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] Two days after independence, the Muslim-majority Murshidabad district in Bengal was moved out of the Dominion of Pakistan and put within the Dominion of India due to a boundary adjustment by the Radcliffe Commission which was aimed at keeping the Hooghly River entirely within India.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] At its inception, Pakistan consisted of two wings, which were separated from each other by around 1,600 kilometres (990 mi) of Indian territory.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] The western wing consisted of a merger of the North-West Frontier Province, West Punjab, Sind Province, and Baluchistan CCP.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] The eastern wing consisted of East Bengal.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] What later became the Princely states of Pakistan chose at first to remain independent.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 1948, Karachi was separated from Sind Province to form the Federal Capital Territory.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 1950, the North-West Frontier Province absorbed the princely states of Amb and Phulra while West Punjab (designated 'West' to distinguish it from India's Punjab in the east) was renamed to simply Punjab.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 1952, the four princely states in the southwest formed the Baluchistan States Union.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 1955, the *One Unit* policy was launched by then-Prime Minister Muhammad Ali Bogra, whereby all the provinces and princely states of the western wing were merged to form the provincial wing of West Pakistan, with Lahore serving as its provincial capital.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] Simultaneously, East Bengal was redesignated as East Pakistan, with Dacca serving as its provincial capital.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] The One Unit policy aimed to reduce expenditure and to eliminate provincial prejudices, but the military coup of 1958 brought difficulties when the first military President, Ayub Khan, abolished the office of the Chief Minister of West Pakistan in favour of Governor rule.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] On 7 September 1958, after four years of negotiations (including six months of intense negotiations), Pakistan purchased the enclave of Gwadar from Oman for ₨.5.5 billion (US$3 million; approximately $22,410,311.42 in 2017).
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] Gwadar formally became a part of Pakistan on 8 December 1958, ending 174 years of Omani rule.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 1960, the federal capital was moved from Karachi to Rawalpindi and in 1961, the Federal Capital Territory was also merged into West Pakistan.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 1966, the capital was again moved to the newly constructed city of Islamabad.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 1962, Dacca was made the legislative capital of the country due to East Pakistan's high population.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 1970, the second military President, Yahya Khan, abolished the political structure of West Pakistan and established four new provinces: Sindh, Punjab, Balochistan and the North-West Frontier Province.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 1971, the Bengali-majority wing of East Pakistan seceded from the Pakistani union following the Bangladesh Liberation War, consequently forming the independent People's Republic of Bangladesh.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 1974, the remaining princely states of Hunza and Nagar were abolished and their territories merged into the Gilgit Agency, following which the Northern Areas were formed.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 1975, portions of the districts of Peshawar and Dera Ismail Khan were separated to form the Federally Administered Tribal Areas.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 1981, the region surrounding Islamabad was separated from Punjab province, and renamed to the Islamabad Capital Territory.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In August 2000, divisions were abolished as part of a plan to restructure local governments, followed by elections in 2001.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] Many of the functions previously handled at a provincial level had been transferred to individual districts and tehsils.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 2008, the government restored the former divisions and appointed commissioners.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 2009, the Northern Areas were renamed to Gilgit-Baltistan, and retained its formal status as an autonomous territory.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 2010, the North-West Frontier Province was formally renamed to Khyber Pakhtunkhwa.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] In 2018, the National Assembly of Pakistan and Khyber Pakhtunkhwa Provincial Assembly passed the historic *FATA Merger Bill* with the Twenty-Fifth Constitutional Amendment.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] On 31 May 2018, the final step in the merger of the Federally Administered Tribal Areas with Khyber Pakhtunkhwa was completed, as then-President Mamnoon Hussain signed the 25th Constitutional Amendment Bill into law.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] The amendment's signing abolished the Federally Administered Tribal Areas as a separate political entity and merged them into the province of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] The Provinces and administrative territories of Pakistan are subdivided into administrative "divisions", Divisional Commissioner is the administrative head of a division.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] The District Coordination Officer is the administrative head of the District Administration.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] They have wide-ranging responsibility for overseeing, improving and directing the approved plans of the District Government.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] The Zila Nazim used to be the executive head of the District Administration until 2010 when the government gave their powers to the District Coordination Officers also.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] Their role is similar to district governor or prefect, with responsibility for implementing government strategy and developing initiatives arising out of it.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] Among the three tiers of local government, tehsil government is the second tier.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] It is where the functions, responsibilities, and authorities of districts government are divided into smaller units, these units are known as "tehsils".
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] The tehsils are used all over Pakistan except Sindh province where the word "taluka" is used instead, although the functions and authorities are the same.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] The head of the Tehsil government is "Tehsil Nazim" who is assisted by the tehsil Naib-Nazim.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] Every tehsil has a Tehsil Municipal Administration, consisting of a tehsil council, Tehsil Nazim, tehsil/taluka municipal officer (TMO), chief officer and other officials of the local council.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] Members of the union council including Union Administrator and Vice Union Administrator are elected through direct elections based on adult franchise and on the basis of joint electorate.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] However, for the election to the reserved seats for women in Zila Council proportionately divided among tehsils or towns shall be all members of the union councils in a tehsil or town.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] It is the responsibility of the Chief Election Commissioner to organize and conduct these elections.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] Between August 1947 and March 1948, the rulers of the following princely states (which had existed alongside but outside British India) acceded their states to Pakistan, giving up control of their external affairs, while all retaining internal self-government, at least to begin with.
[src:aloo-tikki/administrative-units-of-pakistan] This was lost by stages, until by 1974 all of the states had been fully integrated into Pakistan.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] Composed of white or wheat flour and combined with a leavening agent, typically yeast, naan dough develops air pockets that contribute to its fluffy and soft texture.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] Additional ingredients for crafting naan include warm water, salt, ghee and yogurt, with optional additions like milk, egg, or honey.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] Baking powder or baking soda can be used instead of yeast to reduce the preparation time for the bread.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] In the baking process using a tandoor, naan dough is rolled into balls, flattened and pressed against the inner walls, which can reach temperatures up to 480 °C (900 °F).
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] This method allows the bread to be baked within minutes, achieving a spotty browning due to intense heat.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] Naan can be prepared on a stovetop using a tava.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] The pan may be flipped upside down over the flame to achieve browning on the bread's surface.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] Once baked, naan is coated with ghee or butter and served warm.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] This soft and pliable bread accompanies meals, replacing utensils for scooping up sauces, stews, and curries, or with dryer dishes like tandoori chicken.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] The term "naan" comes from Persian *nân* (نان), a generic word for any kind of bread.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] The earliest known English use of the term occurs in an 1803 travelogue written by William Tooke.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] While Tooke and other early sources spelled it "nan", the spelling "naan" has become predominant since the 1970s.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] Naan spread to the Indian subcontinent during the Islamic Delhi Sultanate period.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] The earliest mention of naan in the region comes from the memoirs of Indo-Persian Sufi poet Amir Khusrau living in India during the 1300s AD.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] Khusrau mentions two kinds of naan eaten by Muslim nobles; Naan-e-Tunuk and Naan-e-Tanuri.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] Naan-e-Tunuk was a light or thin bread, while Naan-e-Tanuri was a heavy bread and was baked in the tandoor.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] During India’s Mughal era in the 1520s, naan was a delicacy that only nobles and royal families enjoyed because of the lengthy process of making leavened bread and because the art of making naan was a revered skill known by few.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] The Ain-i-Akbari, a record of the third Mughal emperor’s reign, refers to naan being eaten with kebabs or kheema in it.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] By the 1700s, naan had reached the masses in Mughal cultural centers in South Asia.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] In Indonesia, naan is a popular alternative to rice among the Indians, Arabs, Malays, Acehnese and the Minangkabaus, similar though not the same as roti or roti canai which was introduced from Tamils.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] This dish is known as roti naan or roti nan, and is cooked using Indonesian spices such as garlic.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] The Jingzhou style of guokui, a flatbread prepared inside a cylindrical charcoal oven much like a tandoor, has been described as "Chinese naan".
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] It is also an integral part of Uyghur cuisine and is known in Chinese as 饢 (*náng*).
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] After being promoted by Kandagawa Sekizai Shoukou in 1968, which is now the sole domestic manufacturer of tandoors, naan is now widely available in Indian-style curry restaurants in Japan, where naan is typically free-flow.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] Some restaurants bake ingredients such as cheese, garlic, onions, and potatoes into the naan, or cover it with toppings like a pizza.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] In France, the classical naan has been revisited with cheese, to create Cheese Naan in Paris in the 1970s.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] The most likely origin is attributed to André Risser, who, concerned about the French reception of Indian cuisine in 1967, decided to fill naan with cheese spread.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] Another hypothesis attributes the creation of the variant, in Paris in 1976, to an Indian family from Bombay.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] In 1799, the word naan was introduced into the English language by historian and clergyman William Tooke.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] Today, naan can be found worldwide in restaurants serving South Asian and Middle Eastern cuisine, and it is available in many supermarkets.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] Fusion cuisine has introduced new dishes that incorporate naan, including naan pizza and naan tacos and even huevos rancheros (an egg dish) served over naan.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] Naan pizza is a type of pizza where naan is used as the crust instead of the traditional pizza dough.
[src:aloo-tikki/afghan-bread] Chefs such as Nigella Lawson, and supermarkets such as Wegmans offer recipes for people to make their own naan pizza at home, though it is certainly not traditional.
[src:aloo-tikki/ajiaco] The exact origin of this dish has been debated by scholars.
[src:aloo-tikki/ajiaco] In the Cuban city of Camagüey, the San Juan festival begins with the making and serving of ajiaco.
[src:aloo-tikki/ajiaco] *La Calle* magazine of Cuba stated that the inhabitants of the village of Santa María de Puerto del Príncipe began the tradition of making ajiaco using their own cooking ingredients, donations from passersby, surplus from farmers, and surplus slave provisions.
[src:aloo-tikki/ajiaco] Ajiaco is believed to have become popular in Cuba during the 16th century, particularly among rural Cubans, although it was occasionally enjoyed by the upper class.
[src:aloo-tikki/ajiaco] In the Colombian capital of Bogotá, ajiaco is a popular dish typically made with chicken, three varieties of potatoes, and the *Galinsoga parviflora* herb, commonly referred to in Colombia as *guasca* or *guascas*, and in the U.S., where it is considered a weed, as gallant soldier.
[src:aloo-tikki/ajiaco] It can be garnished with capers, avocado slices, pieces of corn on the cob, or cream.
[src:aloo-tikki/ajiaco] In Cuba, ajiaco is a hearty stew made from beef, pork, chicken, vegetables, and a variety of starchy roots and tubers classified as *viandas*.
[src:aloo-tikki/ajiaco] In Peru, ajiaco is a quite different dish of potatoes cooked with garlic, a mix of dried yellow and red chilies (aji mirasol and aji panca), hierba buena, and huacatay, generally accompanied by rice and stewed chicken or rabbit.
[src:aloo-tikki/ajiaco] In Chile, ajiaco is a food of northern origin, it contains beef, onion, carrot and paprika, garlic and colored chili, potatoes and seasonings, powdered rib broth and coriander/parsley.
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] The word *Axone* is from the Naga Sümi language, and is a combination of two words.
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] *Axo* means "aroma" or "smell" and *ne* or *nhe* (similar word "tho") means "deep" or "strong".
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] So it can be literally translated as "deep smell" or "strong smell".
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] It is prepared year-round from soybeans by people of all tribes, but most notably the Sümi Nagas of Nagaland.
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] Soybeans grow at an altitude of 1,500 m and in rainy conditions, making them well suited for the Naga hills.
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] They are also a protein-rich legume in an otherwise traditionally protein-sparse diet.
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] As with the majority of fermented products in Nagaland, it is considered to be ready when it "smells right".
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] The soybeans are then placed in a wooden pestle and mashed with a mortar.
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] They are not mashed completely but instead crushed comparably to garlic.
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] A handful is then scooped up and placed in the center of a banana leaf, its edges closed to make a parcel.
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] The package is sold or stored next to the fire and can be used immediately or kept for some weeks, darkening in color each day.
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] Axone fermentation results in proteolysis giving it a distinctive umami taste.
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] *Axone* is then used in a wide variety of dishes.
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] Two examples are fire-smoked pork and *axone* and *nula* (snails with *axone*).
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] A 2019 Indian Hindi/English film titled *Axone*, directed by Nicholas Kharkongor, deals with a day in the lives of a group of friends getting ready for a wedding and cooking axone in a Delhi neighborhood which does not allow them to cook axone because of its strong smell.
[src:aloo-tikki/akhuni] Piak of Arunachal Pradesh, Nepali kinema, tungrymbai of Meghalaya, hawaijaar of Manipur and bekang um of Mizoram.
[src:aloo-tikki/aloo-tikki] Because of the broad geographical distribution of Indian people throughout the world, a number of variations on this dish exist.
[src:aloo-tikki/aloo-tikki] In Maharashtra, a popular version of aloo tikki is served with a spicy curry and various chutneys.
[src:aloo-tikki/aloo-tikki] It is called ragda pattice and is sold at various chaat stalls throughout the city and especially on Chowpatti Beach.
[src:aloo-tikki/aloo-tikki] The aloo tikki in this region is made of mainly locally grown spices such as turmeric, whereas in Bangalore, more coriander is used.
[src:aloo-tikki/aloo-tikki] In the United Kingdom, vegetable tikki is available from delicatessen counters at various shops.
[src:aloo-tikki/aloo-tikki] Some North Indian dhabas or café-style eateries will sandwich the aloo in bread.
